{"id":"1808.08704","submitter":"Gerard Letac G.","authors":"G\\'erard Letac","title":"Is the Sibuya distribution a progeny?","comments":"6 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For $0<a<1$ the Sibuya distribution $s_a$ is concentrated on the set\n$\\mathbb{N}^+$ of positive integers and is defined by the generating function\n$\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty}s_a(n)z^n=1-(1-z)^a.$ A distribution $q$ on $\\mathbb{N}^+$\nis called a progeny if there exists a Galton-Watson process\n  $(Z_n)_{n\\geq 0}$ such that $Z_0=1$, such that $\\mathbb{E}(Z_1)\\leq 1$ and\nsuch that $q$ is the distribution of $\\sum _{n=0}^{\\infty}Z_n. $ The paper\nproves that $s_a$ is a progeny if and only if $\\frac{1}{2}\\leq a<1.$ The point\nis to find the values of $b=1/a$ such that the power series expansion of\n$u(1-(1-u)^b)^{-1}$ has non negative coefficients. The proof is not short, but\nelementary.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 27 Aug 2018 06:59:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-28"}
